He's got the sharpest mind        
 on the ship.                      
          He's sharp. all right.

18
00:01:03.897 --> 00:01:05.690
He knows everything Queeg did.

19
00:01:06.316 --> 00:01:08.068
I'm sure he does.

20
00:01:16.743 --> 00:01:19.996
The trial counsel             
      will state the charge         
      and specification.

21
00:01:20.789 --> 00:01:23.083
Charge one. mutiny.

22
00:01:23.124 --> 00:01:26.711
Violation of Article 94.      
      Uniform Code                  
      of Military Justice.

23
00:01:26.753 --> 00:01:29.506
Specification: In that        
      Lieutenant Stephen Maryk.

24
00:01:29.547 --> 00:01:33.426
while serving             
          as executive officer      
          aboard the USS   Caine.

25
00:01:33.468 --> 00:01:38.181
did on December 18th. 2022.   
      commit an act of mutiny.

26
00:01:38.223 --> 00:01:41.893
Lieutenant Maryk willfully.       
 and without proper authority.

27
00:01:41.935 --> 00:01:44.354
and without                       
 justifiable cause

28
00:01:44.395 --> 00:01:47.273
did relieve from duty         
      Lieutenant Commander          
      Philip Francis Queeg.

29
00:01:47.315 --> 00:01:50.110
then serving                  
      as the duly appointed         
      commanding officer

30
00:01:50.151 --> 00:01:51.485
of the USS   Caine.

31
00:01:51.527 --> 00:01:54.280
who was then                  
      in lawful exercise            
      of his command.

32
00:01:55.156 --> 00:01:56.574
How do you plead?

33
00:01:57.158 --> 00:01:58.326
Not guilty.

34
00:01:58.368 --> 00:02:00.161
Defense will stipulate            
 that Lieutenant Maryk

35
00:02:00.203 --> 00:02:02.580
was serving                       
 as executive officer              
 aboard the USS   Caine.

36
00:02:02.622 --> 00:02:04.332
18 December. 2022.

37
00:02:04.374 --> 00:02:08.086
Trial counsel.                
      you may call                  
      your first witness.

38
00:02:09.002 --> 00:02:11.506
Call Lieutenant Commander Queeg.

39
00:02:21.599 --> 00:02:25.061
Do you solemnly swear         
      that the evidence you give    
      shall be the truth.

40
00:02:25.103 --> 00:02:27.480
the whole truth               
      and nothing but the truth.    
      so help you God?

41
00:02:27.522 --> 00:02:29.149
I do.

42
00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:30.650
Be seated.

43
00:02:36.531 --> 00:02:38.825
[prosecutor]              
          State your name. rank     
          and present position.

44
00:02:38.867 --> 00:02:42.495
Philip Francis Queeg.             
 Lieutenant Commander.             
 United States Navy.

45
00:02:42.537 --> 00:02:46.332
currently attached                
 to Headquarters. Fifth Fleet.     
 awaiting reassignment.

46
00:02:47.041 --> 00:02:49.627
Do you recognize 
                  the accused?

47
00:02:49.668 --> 00:02:51.588
[Queeg] Yes.

48
00:02:51.629 --> 00:02:54.132
Lieutenant Maryk.     
              US Navy.

49
00:02:54.174 --> 00:02:58.553
Commander Queeg.                  
 on December 18th. 2022.

50
00:02:58.595 --> 00:03:00.471
were you in command               
 of the USS   Caine?

51
00:03:00.513 --> 00:03:02.015
Yes. I was.

52
00:03:02.515 --> 00:03:04.767
What type of vessel   
              is the   Caine?

53
00:03:04.809 --> 00:03:08.980
Well. her official            
      designation is an MCM--       
      mine countermeasures ship.

54
00:03:09.022 --> 00:03:11.065
And what is           
              her primary mission?

55
00:03:11.107 --> 00:03:14.485
Well. the   Caine                   
 is designed to detect             
 and neutralize sea-based mines.

56
00:03:14.527 --> 00:03:16.070
We conduct                
          minesweeping operations

57
00:03:16.112 --> 00:03:18.198
as directed anywhere 
              in the Persian Gulf.

58
00:03:18.239 --> 00:03:20.450
with an emphasis              
      on the Straits of Hormuz.

59
00:03:20.491 --> 00:03:24.370
Commander.                
          on December 18th. 2022.

60
00:03:24.412 --> 00:03:26.873
were you relieved of command 
      of the   Caine?

61
00:03:26.915 --> 00:03:28.958
Yes.

62
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:30.460
By whom?

63
00:03:30.501 --> 00:03:32.503
The accused.          
              Lieutenant Maryk.

64
00:03:32.545 --> 00:03:35.882
[prosecutor] Was this     
          a standard watch change?

65
00:03:35.924 --> 00:03:38.843
No. it was            
              totally irregular.

66
00:03:38.885 --> 00:03:40.720
How would you     
                  describe it?      
                  [scoffs]

67
00:03:40.762 --> 00:03:46.017
Well. the most charitable     
      description would be          
      that it was an incident.

68
00:03:46.059 --> 00:03:48.394
a regrettable incident    
          of the temporary

69
00:03:48.436 --> 00:03:50.980
and total collapse        
          of military discipline.

70
00:03:51.022 --> 00:03:55.151
Commander. please relate      
      all the facts that bear       
      on this unauthorized relief.

71
00:03:56.277 --> 00:03:58.321
Okay. well.

72
00:03:58.363 --> 00:04:01.741
the   Caine   sortied from Bahrain    
 on December 16th.

73
00:04:01.783 --> 00:04:05.453
Our mission was to sweep          
 for mines from the Persian Gulf   
 through the Straits of Hormuz.

74
00:04:05.495 --> 00:04:09.290
When a cyclone came along         
 the operation was canceled.

75
00:04:09.332 --> 00:04:11.626
and the boat                      
 started to maneuver               
 to evade the storm.

76
00:04:11.668 --> 00:04:13.878
The storm                         
 was traveling due west.

77
00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:16.714
[prosecutor]                  
      What was the date and time    
      of that course change?

78
00:04:16.755 --> 00:04:20.051
Well. that would be               
 early morning                     
 of the 18th. ma'am.

79
00:04:20.093 --> 00:04:22.762
And as I say. the storm was       
 pretty bad at that point.

80
00:04:22.804 --> 00:04:24.806
Visibility was almost zero.

81
00:04:24.847 --> 00:04:28.184
Couldn't see                      
 any of the other ships            
 in the detachment.

82
00:04:28.226 --> 00:04:31.145
We were sailing blind through     
 the rain and the spray.

83
00:04:31.187 --> 00:04:32.981
and with the wind                 
 and the sea and all.

84
00:04:33.022 --> 00:04:35.108
we had to maneuver                
 using engines and rudders

85
00:04:35.149 --> 00:04:37.110
to hold the evasion course        
 that had been ordered.

86
00:04:37.151 --> 00:04:39.445
But w-we were doing fine.

87
00:04:39.487 --> 00:04:43.116
My executive officer. however.    
 pretty early in the game.

88
00:04:43.157 --> 00:04:46.119
began to show                     
 unusual symptoms                  
 of nervousness.

89
00:04:46.159 --> 00:04:48.079
What were         
                  these symptoms?

90
00:04:48.121 --> 00:04:50.248
Well. for example. he started     
 talking pretty early--

91
00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:53.960
Couldn't have been more           
 than half an hour after           
 the ship started running south--

92
00:04:54.002 --> 00:04:57.463
that we needed                    
 to operate independently          
 and come around to the north.

93
00:04:57.505 --> 00:04:59.549
Why did he want   
                  to do that?

94
00:04:59.590 --> 00:05:01.676
Well. to give you the picture.    
 the cyclone was coming at us      
 from the east.

95
00:05:01.718 --> 00:05:03.303
We were on                
          the western edge of it.

96
00:05:03.344 --> 00:05:06.264
which means where we were.        
 the wind was from due north.

97
00:05:06.306 --> 00:05:10.768
Now. the   Commodore.   of course.    
 was running south with the wind   
 to get out of the storm's path.

98
00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:14.105
which was in accordance with      
 all existing storm doctrine.

99
00:05:14.147 --> 00:05:18.401
My exec. however.                 
 insisted that our ship            
 was on the verge of foundering

100
00:05:18.443 --> 00:05:20.403
and that we had better            
 turn into the wind.

101
00:05:20.445 --> 00:05:23.406
wh-which was the north.           
 if we were to survive.

102
00:05:23.448 --> 00:05:27.118
Now... [chuckles]                 
 ...of course. we weren't          
 in that bad of shape.

103
00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:29.203
And that's what                   
 I mean by nervousness.

104
00:05:29.245 --> 00:05:31.122
What was your objection   
          to coming north.

105
00:05:31.164 --> 00:05:33.082
as your executive officer     
      suggested?

106
00:05:33.124 --> 00:05:35.668
Well. everything was wrong        
 with that idea                    
 that could be wrong with it.

107
00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:39.881
I mean. in the first place.       
 my orders were to proceed south.

108
00:05:39.922 --> 00:05:42.425
My ship wasn't in danger.     
      It--

109
00:05:42.467 --> 00:05:44.761
It was functioning normally.

110
00:05:44.802 --> 00:05:48.598
Uh. to drop out of station    
      and act independently         
      under those circumstances

111
00:05:48.639 --> 00:05:50.141
is out of the question.

112
00:05:50.183 --> 00:05:52.018
And to come around north

113
00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:54.354
would be to head              
      the ship directly into        
      the heart of the cyclone.

114
00:05:54.395 --> 00:05:59.317
It was a senseless suggestion     
 and. under the circumstances.     
 almost suicidal.

115
00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:02.070
I have since checked          
      all of my decisions           
      of December 18th

116
00:06:02.111 --> 00:06:04.072
with the finest               
      ship handlers I know.

117
00:06:04.113 --> 00:06:06.115
ranking all the way up        
      to rear admiral.

118
00:06:06.157 --> 00:06:10.536
and unanimously they agree    
      that the only course          
      in that situation was south.

119
00:06:11.662 --> 00:06:14.916
[prosecutor]                      
 Commander. your last remark       
 was hearsay.

120
00:06:14.957 --> 00:06:16.459
Oh. I'm-- I'm sorry.

121
00:06:16.501 --> 00:06:18.669
I'm not up                    
      on these legal distinctions

122
00:06:18.711 --> 00:06:20.254
as well as I should be.       
      I guess.

123
00:06:20.296 --> 00:06:22.757
[prosecutor]                      
 It's perfectly all right.

124
00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:25.885
Will defense counsel move         
 to strike out the part of         
 the testimony which was hearsay?

125
00:06:25.927 --> 00:06:27.095
All right. so move.

126
00:06:27.136 --> 00:06:28.971
[prosecutor]                      
 Please continue.

127
00:06:29.013 --> 00:06:32.892
Well. i-it's just that Maryk's    
 insistence on us coming around

128
00:06:32.933 --> 00:06:36.771
became more and more strident     
 as the weather deteriorated.

129
00:06:36.813 --> 00:06:38.898
I finally became          
          concerned about him

130
00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:41.025
when suddenly             
          he moved towards me

131
00:06:41.067 --> 00:06:44.529
and out of the blue said          
 I was on the sick list            
 and that he was relieving me.

132
00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:47.657
I-I-- To be honest.           
      I couldn't believe my ears.

133
00:06:47.698 --> 00:06:49.742
Took me a moment          
          to catch on.

134
00:06:49.784 --> 00:06:52.495
It wasn't until               
      he started shouting orders    
      at the officer of the deck

135
00:06:52.537 --> 00:06:55.415
and started countermanding    
      my instructions

136
00:06:55.456 --> 00:06:59.752
that I-I did begin to         
      realize what was going on.

137
00:06:59.794 --> 00:07:01.504
Commander.                        
 can you recall anything

138
00:07:01.546 --> 00:07:04.549
that could have provoked          
 your executive officer's act?

139
00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:06.509
Truthfully. no.

140
00:07:06.551 --> 00:07:09.429
I don't think                 
      my bearing or manner          
      had anything to do with it.

141
00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:13.182
Look... it was            
          a pretty scary situation 
          in that wheelhouse.

142
00:07:13.224 --> 00:07:16.185
Winds were force ten to 12.   
      screeching and all.

143
00:07:16.227 --> 00:07:18.396
and the waves             
          were mountainous.

144
00:07:18.438 --> 00:07:21.524
The barometer had dropped     
      about as low as it's ever     
      been in US Navy history.

145
00:07:21.566 --> 00:07:24.026
and we took               
          a very bad roll.

146
00:07:24.068 --> 00:07:25.820
And I mean a very bad one.

147
00:07:25.862 --> 00:07:28.030
I've done a lot           
          of North Atlantic         
          rolling too.

148
00:07:28.072 --> 00:07:30.032
I just think that Maryk       
      simply went into a panic.

149
00:07:30.074 --> 00:07:31.742
[prosecutor] 
                      Mmm.

150
00:07:31.784 --> 00:07:34.537
Was the   Caine     
                  in grave danger   
                  at that time?

151
00:07:34.579 --> 00:07:37.874
Well. I-I wouldn't say that. 
      no. ma'am.

152
00:07:37.915 --> 00:07:41.252
I-I thought                       
 we righted ourselves very nicely 
 out of that bad roll.

153
00:07:41.294 --> 00:07:45.715
He repeatedly tried to            
 order me off the bridge.          
 but I stayed right where I was

154
00:07:45.756 --> 00:07:49.260
and gave him orders           
      only as I thought necessary   
      for the safety of the ship.

155
00:07:49.302 --> 00:07:52.972
I-In the situation.               
 I thought that the chief hazard

156
00:07:53.014 --> 00:07:55.975
would be any further          
      act of frenzy on his part.

157
00:07:56.017 --> 00:07:59.979
And to the extent that        
      the   Caine   did come through    
      that storm safely.

158
00:08:00.021 --> 00:08:04.942
despite the unprecedented... 
      [chuckles] ...running amok    
      of my executive officer.

159
00:08:04.984 --> 00:08:09.489
I believe that my handling    
      of the emergency              
      was the correct one.

160
00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:12.658
Did Maryk cite            
          any authority at all      
          when he relieved you?

161
00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:15.036
Oh. he mumbled something          
 about our Article 1108.

162
00:08:15.077 --> 00:08:17.079
I didn't even catch it            
 at the time.

163
00:08:17.121 --> 00:08:20.291
It wasn't till later              
 that he said his authority

164
00:08:20.332 --> 00:08:23.753
was Article 1108          
          of Navy Regulations.

165
00:08:23.794 --> 00:08:26.881
And were you familiar             
 with these articles?              
                  Certainly.

166
00:08:26.923 --> 00:08:29.967
In substance.                     
 what do they provide?

167
00:08:30.009 --> 00:08:33.136
