00:40:42.314 --> 00:40:43.983
If you're on                  
      the verge of sinking.

860
00:40:44.024 --> 00:40:46.068
you about as bad off          
      as you can get.

861
00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:47.653
Mind you. you said            
      worst-case scenario.

862
00:40:47.695 --> 00:40:52.324
I did. sir.                       
 Thank you very much.              
 No further questions.

863
00:40:52.366 --> 00:40:54.660
Captain.                  
          who. in your opinion.     
          is the best judge

864
00:40:54.702 --> 00:40:57.580
as to whether a ship is in        
 the worst-case scenario?

865
00:40:57.621 --> 00:41:01.292
There's only one judge.           
 The commanding officer.

866
00:41:01.333 --> 00:41:03.169
Why. sir?

867
00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:06.505
The Navy made him captain         
 'cause his knowledge              
 of the sea and of ships

868
00:41:06.547 --> 00:41:09.383
is better than anyone else's      
 on the ship.

869
00:41:09.425 --> 00:41:14.138
It's very common                  
 for some subordinate officers     
 to think the ship is sinking

870
00:41:14.180 --> 00:41:17.224
when all that's happening         
 is a little weather.

871
00:41:17.266 --> 00:41:20.060
Well. don't you think. sir.       
 that when his subordinates

872
00:41:20.102 --> 00:41:22.062
all agree that the ship           
 is going down

873
00:41:22.104 --> 00:41:23.814
that the captain ought            
 to listen to them?

874
00:41:23.856 --> 00:41:25.816
Negative.

875
00:41:25.858 --> 00:41:29.153
Panic is a common hazard 
          at sea.

876
00:41:29.195 --> 00:41:31.322
The highest function of command   
 is to override

877
00:41:31.363 --> 00:41:34.575
and listen to nothing     
          but the voice of his own 
          professional judgment.

878
00:41:35.868 --> 00:41:38.162
Call Dr. Joan Lundeen.

879
00:41:43.042 --> 00:41:45.169
State your name. rank     
          and present station.

880
00:41:45.211 --> 00:41:47.338
Lieutenant Commander              
 Joan Lundeen.

881
00:41:47.379 --> 00:41:49.965
Medical Corps. US Navy.           
 Head of Psychiatry.

882
00:41:50.007 --> 00:41:52.176
US Naval Hospital.            
      San Francisco.

883
00:41:52.218 --> 00:41:55.179
Were you the head of              
 the medical board that examined   
 Lieutenant Commander Queeg?

884
00:41:55.221 --> 00:41:56.555
I was.

885
00:41:56.597 --> 00:41:59.975
And how long                      
 did your examination last.        
 Doctor?

886
00:42:00.017 --> 00:42:03.687
We had the commander              
 under constant observation        
 and testing for three weeks.

887
00:42:03.729 --> 00:42:05.773
[Challee]                         
 And what was the finding          
 of the board?

888
00:42:05.814 --> 00:42:08.817
Commander Queeg was discharged    
 with a clean bill of health.

889
00:42:08.859 --> 00:42:13.572
Doctor. is it possible        
      that two months ago.          
      on December 18th.

890
00:42:13.614 --> 00:42:16.367
he was in such a state    
          of psychotic collapse

891
00:42:16.408 --> 00:42:19.495
that relieving him    
              from naval command    
              would be justified?

892
00:42:19.537 --> 00:42:20.788
No.

893
00:42:20.829 --> 00:42:22.665
Is it possible    
                  for a sane man

894
00:42:22.706 --> 00:42:26.627
to perform offensive.     
          disagreeable.             
          foolish acts?

895
00:42:26.669 --> 00:42:28.379
It happens every day.

896
00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:31.006
We didn't find                
      that the commander            
      was a perfect officer.

897
00:42:31.048 --> 00:42:34.718
Yet. you still say        
          that to relieve him       
          from naval command

898
00:42:34.760 --> 00:42:37.888
because of mental illness     
      would be unjustified?

899
00:42:37.930 --> 00:42:41.058
Completely unjustified.

900
00:42:41.725 --> 00:42:43.269
Thank you.

901
00:42:43.769 --> 00:42:45.980
Dr. Lundeen.

902
00:42:46.021 --> 00:42:48.023
my background is legal.       
      not medical.

903
00:42:48.065 --> 00:42:51.569
so I hope you'll bear with me     
 as I try to clarify               
 some technical terms.

904
00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:53.320
Of course.

905
00:42:53.362 --> 00:42:57.366
I'm going to ask some             
 pretty elementary questions.      
                      All right.

906
00:42:57.408 --> 00:43:00.077
Would you say Commander Queeg     
 is absolutely normal?

907
00:43:00.119 --> 00:43:01.912
[chuckles]

908
00:43:01.954 --> 00:43:05.291
Well. normality. you know.    
      is a fiction in psychiatry.   
 Mmm.

909
00:43:05.332 --> 00:43:08.669
No adult is without problems 
      except a happy imbecile.

910
00:43:08.711 --> 00:43:10.838
What are                      
      Commander Queeg's problems?

911
00:43:10.879 --> 00:43:14.508
You might say his             
      overall problem is one of     
      an inferiority complex

912
00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:16.635
generated                     
      by an unhappy childhood

913
00:43:16.677 --> 00:43:19.972
and aggravated                    
 by certain adult experiences.

914
00:43:20.014 --> 00:43:22.308
Unhappy childhood                 
 in what way?

915
00:43:22.349 --> 00:43:26.562
Divorced parents.         
          financial trouble.

916
00:43:26.604 --> 00:43:28.105
problems at school.

917
00:43:28.147 --> 00:43:30.482
And the aggravating factors   
      in adult life?

918
00:43:31.775 --> 00:43:33.235
In his adult life.

919
00:43:33.277 --> 00:43:35.529
the commander is troubled         
 by his low standing

920
00:43:35.571 --> 00:43:37.906
in his academy class              
 and other such factors.

921
00:43:37.948 --> 00:43:39.783
but he has                        
 become well-adjusted.

922
00:43:39.825 --> 00:43:42.911
Mmm. Can you describe             
 the nature of that adjustment?

923
00:43:42.953 --> 00:43:46.457
His identity as a naval officer   
 is the essential factor.

924
00:43:46.498 --> 00:43:48.917
It's the key                      
 to his personal security.

925
00:43:48.959 --> 00:43:52.463
Therefore.                        
 he has a fixed anxiety            
 about protecting his standing.

926
00:43:52.504 --> 00:43:54.465
That would account            
      for his harshness.

927
00:43:54.506 --> 00:43:56.592
Would he be slow                  
 to admit mistakes?

928
00:43:56.634 --> 00:43:59.303
Yes. of course.               
      There's nothing               
      unbalanced in that.

929
00:43:59.345 --> 00:44:02.514
Oh. really? I mean.           
      would he be a perfectionist?

930
00:44:02.556 --> 00:44:04.600
Such a personality        
          would be.

931
00:44:04.642 --> 00:44:06.310
Inclined to hound     
              his subordinates

932
00:44:06.352 --> 00:44:07.895
over the smallest         
          little details.

933
00:44:07.936 --> 00:44:11.440
Any mistake           
              of a subordinate      
              is intolerable

934
00:44:11.482 --> 00:44:13.525
because it might cause him harm.

935
00:44:13.567 --> 00:44:17.529
Yet he will not admit mistakes    
 that he makes himself.

936
00:44:17.571 --> 00:44:21.742
You might say             
          that he revises reality   
          in his own mind

937
00:44:21.784 --> 00:44:23.661
so he comes out blameless.

938
00:44:23.702 --> 00:44:27.456
Doctor. isn't                 
      distortion of reality         
      a symptom of mental illness?

939
00:44:27.498 --> 00:44:30.250
It's a question of degree.

940
00:44:30.292 --> 00:44:32.628
Each one of us        
              has our own reality.

941
00:44:32.670 --> 00:44:37.007
Yes. Doctor. but doesn't          
 Commander Queeg distort reality   
 more. say. than you do?

942
00:44:37.049 --> 00:44:39.301
Yes. that's his weakness.

943
00:44:39.343 --> 00:44:41.261
Other people              
          have other weaknesses.

944
00:44:41.303 --> 00:44:43.430
It's definitely           
          not disabling.

945
00:44:43.472 --> 00:44:48.519
Well. if he's criticized.     
      would he think he was         
      being unjustly persecuted?

946
00:44:49.353 --> 00:44:51.271
It's all one pattern.

947
00:44:51.313 --> 00:44:55.109
all stemming                      
 from one basic premise            
 that he must try to be perfect.

948
00:44:55.150 --> 00:44:56.819
Inclined to stubbornness. then.

949
00:44:56.860 --> 00:45:00.322
Well. you'll have             
      a certain rigidity            
      of personality

950
00:45:00.364 --> 00:45:02.366
in such an individual.

951
00:45:02.408 --> 00:45:04.702
His inner insecurity          
      stops him from admitting

952
00:45:04.743 --> 00:45:07.663
that those who differ         
      from him may be right.

953
00:45:07.705 --> 00:45:12.960
Doctor. you just testified that   
 the following symptoms exist      
 in Commander Queeg's behavior.

954
00:45:13.001 --> 00:45:14.670
We have rigidity                  
 of personality.

955
00:45:14.712 --> 00:45:16.422
We have feelings                  
 of persecution.

956
00:45:16.463 --> 00:45:18.507
We have                           
 unreasonable suspicion.

957
00:45:18.549 --> 00:45:20.217
We have withdrawal                
 from reality.

958
00:45:20.259 --> 00:45:22.261
We have performance anxiety.

959
00:45:22.302 --> 00:45:24.805
We have an unreal basic premise

960
00:45:24.847 --> 00:45:27.683
and an obsessive sense            
 of self-righteousness.

961
00:45:27.725 --> 00:45:31.061
All mild. sir.                
      All well-compensated.

962
00:45:31.103 --> 00:45:33.105
Yes. Doctor. yes.

963
00:45:33.147 --> 00:45:37.276
But is there                      
 an inclusive psychiatric term.    
 one label for this syndrome?

964
00:45:37.317 --> 00:45:40.154
Syndrome? Who said anything       
 about a syndrome?

965
00:45:40.195 --> 00:45:44.700
You're misusing a term.           
 There's no syndrome               
 because there's no disease.

966
00:45:44.742 --> 00:45:46.660
I'll rephrase it.

967
00:45:46.702 --> 00:45:48.871
Do these symptoms     
              fall into

968
00:45:48.912 --> 00:45:53.000
a single pattern              
      of neurotic disturbance.      
      a common psychiatric class?

969
00:45:53.041 --> 00:45:55.544
I know                    
          what you're getting at.   
 Well?

970
00:45:55.586 --> 00:45:59.840
It's a paranoid personality.      
 but that is not                   
 a disabling affliction.

971
00:45:59.882 --> 00:46:02.092
Doctor--                          
 A what personality.               
 Doctor?

972
00:46:02.134 --> 00:46:04.011
Paranoid.

973
00:46:04.052 --> 00:46:07.181
A paranoid?       
              Yes. paranoid.

974
00:46:09.725 --> 00:46:12.728
Um. Doctor. in a--

975
00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:17.941
in a paranoid personality.    
      like Commander Queeg's.

976
00:46:17.983 --> 00:46:19.860
would he-- I'm--

977
00:46:19.902 --> 00:46:22.070
I'm gonna put this to you     
      hypothetically.

978
00:46:22.112 --> 00:46:24.573
Can a man have                    
 a paranoid personality

979
00:46:24.615 --> 00:46:27.159
that would not disable him    
      for subordinate duties.

980
00:46:27.201 --> 00:46:28.786
but would disable him     
          for command?

981
00:46:28.827 --> 00:46:30.954
It's conceivable.

982
00:46:30.996 --> 00:46:34.166
And is the disabling factor   
      likely to be detected         
      in a personal interview?

983
00:46:34.208 --> 00:46:36.210
With a skilled        
              psychiatrist. yes.

984
00:46:36.251 --> 00:46:38.962
Why? I mean.                      
 why is a psychiatrist needed?

985
00:46:39.004 --> 00:46:41.965
Can't an educated. intelligent    
 person detect a paranoid?

986
00:46:42.007 --> 00:46:44.885
Well. you evidently           
      aren't too well acquainted    
      with the pattern.

987
00:46:44.927 --> 00:46:47.346
The distinguishing mark   
          of this neurosis

988
00:46:47.387 --> 00:46:51.809
is the extreme plausibility   
      and a most convincing normal 
      manner on the surface.

989
00:46:51.850 --> 00:46:54.311
particularly              
          in self-justification.

990
00:46:54.353 --> 00:46:56.271
Self-justification.

991
00:46:56.313 --> 00:46:57.981
Thank you. Doctor.

992
00:46:59.107 --> 00:47:00.484
No further questions.

993
00:47:00.526 --> 00:47:02.820
[officer] The court wishes    
      to clear up one point.

994
00:47:02.861 --> 00:47:07.574
Doctor. is...                     
 is such a thing possible--

995
00:47:07.616 --> 00:47:10.285
Well. let me put it this way.

996
00:47:10.327 --> 00:47:12.162
Let's say that a man              
 with a mild condition

997
00:47:12.204 --> 00:47:16.083
is not disabled for all           
 the usual stresses of command.

998
00:47:16.124 --> 00:47:20.838
Now let's say those stresses      
 are multiplied manifold           
 by an extreme emergency.

999
00:47:20.879 --> 00:47:23.799
Would there then be a tendency    
 to make erroneous judgments?

1000
00:47:23.841 --> 00:47:25.551
There might be. sir.

1001
00:47:25.592 --> 00:47:28.720
Of course. extreme stress         
 does that to almost anybody.

1002
00:47:28.762 --> 00:47:30.722
It's not supposed to do it        
 to commanding officers.

1003
00:47:30.764 --> 00:47:34.977
No. but practically speaking.     
 sir. they're human.

1004
00:47:38.564 --> 00:47:41.149
State your name. rank     
          and present station.

1005
00:47:41.191 --> 00:47:43.902
Allen Bird. MD.                   
 US Navy Reserve.

1006
00:47:43.944 --> 00:47:46.905
I was called to serve on          
 the psychiatric evaluation team.

1007
00:47:46.947 --> 00:47:49.408
Was this the board that       
      was headed by Dr. Lundeen

1008
00:47:49.449 --> 00:47:52.744
which recently inquired into 
      the mental health of          
      Lieutenant Commander Queeg?

1009
00:47:52.786 --> 00:47:54.955
Yes.                  
 And what was the finding          
 of the board?

1010
00:47:54.997 --> 00:47:58.125
We found that the commander   
      is mentally fit               
      for command now

1011
00:47:58.166 --> 00:48:00.544
and has never been unfit.

1012
00:48:00.586 --> 00:48:03.380
Did you find any indication       
 that Commander Queeg

1013
00:48:03.422 --> 00:48:06.717
had what is known             
      as a paranoid personality?

1014
00:48:06.758 --> 00:48:10.846
Well. I prefer to call it         
 obsessive personality             
 with paranoid features.

1015
00:48:10.888 --> 00:48:14.933
Right. but this did not       
      indicate mental unfitness.    
          No.

1016
00:48:14.975 --> 00:48:18.186
You agree. Doctor.    
              that Commander Queeg 
              is mentally fit now

1017
00:48:18.228 --> 00:48:20.981
and must have been    
              mentally fit          
              on December 18th

1018
00:48:21.023 --> 00:48:23.275
when he was relieved 
              on the grounds        
              of mental illness?

1019
00:48:23.317 --> 00:48:25.360
That was                          
 our unanimous conclusion.

1020
00:48:25.402 --> 00:48:27.404
Thank you. Doctor.

1021
00:48:27.446 --> 00:48:29.239
[Greenwald]                       
 Dr. Bird.

1022
00:48:29.281 --> 00:48:32.492
do you have any special training 
 in psychoanalysis?

1023
00:48:32.534 --> 00:48:34.369
Yes.

1024
00:48:34.411 --> 00:48:37.164
Okay. and in psychoanalysis. 
      is there such a thing         
      as mental illness?

1025
00:48:37.205 --> 00:48:39.917
There are disturbed people        
 and adjusted people.

1026
00:48:39.958 --> 00:48:41.919
But those terms.              
      "disturbed" and "adjusted."

1027
00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:44.421
they correspond roughly   
          in layman's terms

1028
00:48:44.463 --> 00:48:46.506
to "sick" and "well."     
          as we use them.

1029
00:48:46.548 --> 00:48:48.592
Very roughly. yes.

1030
00:48:48.634 --> 00:48:53.472
Would you say                 
      Commander Queeg suffers       
      from an inferiority complex?

1031
00:48:53.513 --> 00:48:57.225
Yes. but it's...              
      well-compensated.

1032
00:48:57.267 --> 00:48:59.937
Is there a difference     
          between "compensated"     
          and "adjusted"?

1033
00:48:59.978 --> 00:49:01.146
Most definitely.

1034
00:49:01.188 --> 00:49:03.774
Okay. could you please            
 describe that for us?

1035
00:49:03.815 --> 00:49:06.193
Well. let's say               
      a man is suffering

1036
00:49:06.234 --> 00:49:09.863
from some deep-seated         
      psychological disturbance.

1037
00:49:09.905 --> 00:49:13.951
He can compensate             
      by finding outlets            
      for his peculiar drives.

1038
00:49:13.992 --> 00:49:19.164
Okay. So. has Commander Queeg     
 ever been psychoanalyzed?

1039
00:49:19.206 --> 00:49:21.833
No.   
 He's in your terms. then.         
 a disturbed person?

1040
00:49:21.875 --> 00:49:24.711
Yes. he is.                   
      Not disabled. however.        
      by the disturbance.

1041
00:49:24.753 --> 00:49:26.964
Okay. how is he compensated?

1042
00:49:28.215 --> 00:49:29.925
Mainly two ways.

1043
00:49:29.967 --> 00:49:33.053
The paranoid pattern.             
 which is useless                  
 and not desirable.

1044
00:49:33.095 --> 00:49:36.765
and his naval career.             
 which is extremely useful         
 and desirable.

1045
00:49:36.807 --> 00:49:39.643
Yes. Doctor. have you         
      noticed that little thing     
      he does with his hands?

1046
00:49:39.685 --> 00:49:41.395
You mean                          
 rolling the steel balls?          
              Yes.

1047
00:49:41.436 --> 00:49:43.230
Could you describe    
              that for us. please?

1048
00:49:43.271 --> 00:49:45.816
It's an incessant rolling         
 of two marbles in his hand.

1049
00:49:45.857 --> 00:49:48.568
Mm-hmm.               
              Why does he do it?

1050
00:49:48.610 --> 00:49:51.279
Oh. uh. his hands tremble.

1051
00:49:51.321 --> 00:49:54.199
He does it to still his hands     
 and conceal the trembling.

1052
00:49:54.241 --> 00:49:55.492
Why do his hands tremble?

1053
00:49:55.534 --> 00:49:58.704
Inner tension.                    
 It's a surface symptom.

1054
00:49:58.745 --> 00:50:01.206
Doctor. you've testified 
          that Commander Queeg

1055
00:50:01.248 --> 00:50:03.917
is a disturbed.               
      not an adjusted person. yes?

1056
00:50:03.959 --> 00:50:06.336
Yes.                              
          So he is.                 
          in layman's terms. sick.

1057
00:50:06.378 --> 00:50:08.672
Yes?

1058
00:50:08.714 --> 00:50:12.134
I remember agreeing to the        
 rough resemblance of the terms    
 "disturbed" and "sick."

1059
00:50:12.175 --> 00:50:14.594
but by those terms                
 an awful lot of people            
 are sick.

1060
00:50:14.636 --> 00:50:17.639
Yes. Doctor. but this court   
      only has Commander Queeg's    
      sickness at issue.

1061
00:50:17.681 --> 00:50:21.435
If he is sick. how could      
      your board have given him     
      a clean bill of health?

1062
00:50:21.476 --> 00:50:24.938
Y-You're playing on words.        
 We found no disability.

1063
00:50:24.980 --> 00:50:27.357
Doctor. just suppose      
          for an instant

1064
00:50:27.399 --> 00:50:30.986
that the requirements of command 
 are way more severe               
 than you believe them to be.

1065
00:50:31.028 --> 00:50:34.197
Wouldn't even this mild sickness 
 be enough to disable him?

1066
00:50:34.239 --> 00:50:36.658
That's absurdly hypothetical.     
 because--                         
 Oh. is it?

1067
00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:38.827
Have you ever had         
          sea duty. Doctor?         
 No.

1068
00:50:38.869 --> 00:50:41.872
No? How long have you been    
      in the service of the Navy?

1069
00:50:41.913 --> 00:50:43.206
Five months. 
          Five months?

1070
00:50:43.248 --> 00:50:45.876
Five--            
                  Six months.       
          Six. I guess now.

1071
00:50:45.917 --> 00:50:47.919
Six months in the service         
 of the Navy.

1072
00:50:47.961 --> 00:50:51.381
Have you ever had any dealings    
 with ships' captains              
 prior to this case?

1073
00:50:51.423 --> 00:50:52.549
No.                   
                              No?

1074
00:50:52.591 --> 00:50:54.009
Then on what do you base

1075
00:50:54.051 --> 00:50:55.427
your estimate                     
 of the requirements of command?

1076
00:50:55.469 --> 00:50:57.387
My general knowledge.

1077
00:50:57.429 --> 00:51:00.390
Would you say it takes somebody. 
 a person of exceptional ability.

1078
00:51:00.432 --> 00:51:03.310
highly gifted. highly skilled     
 to be a commander                 
 of a naval vessel?

1079
00:51:03.351 --> 00:51:04.728
No.                   
 No. Really?

1080
00:51:04.770 --> 00:51:07.147
Not highly gifted. no.        
 Then what?

1081
00:51:07.189 --> 00:51:09.691
Uh. reasonable responses.     
 "Reasonable"?

1082
00:51:09.733 --> 00:51:11.777
Uh. fairly good               
      intelligence.                 
 "Fairly good"?

1083
00:51:11.818 --> 00:51:14.196
Sufficient training           
      and experience. but--

1084
00:51:14.237 --> 00:51:17.199
Is this enough equipment.     
      say. for a highly skilled     
      psychiatrist?

1085
00:51:17.240 --> 00:51:19.076
Not exactly.

1086
00:51:19.117 --> 00:51:21.328
So in other words.        
          it takes more ability     
          to be a psychiatrist

1087
00:51:21.369 --> 00:51:23.997
than it does to be    
              the commander of      
              a US naval vessel.

1088
00:51:24.039 --> 00:51:26.666
It takes-- That is.           
      uh. different abilities       
      are required.

1089
00:51:26.708 --> 00:51:28.919
You're making the comparison.     
 not I.

1090
00:51:28.960 --> 00:51:31.713
No. Doctor. you're the one        
 that said you don't think         
 Commander Queeg's sickness

1091
00:51:31.755 --> 00:51:34.049
should disable him for command.

1092
00:51:34.091 --> 00:51:37.552
I am suggesting that since        
 you evidently know little about   
 the requirements of command.

1093
00:51:37.594 --> 00:51:39.429
that you may be wrong         
      in your conclusion.

1094
00:51:39.471 --> 00:51:41.932
Well. I reject                
      your suggestion.              
                  Oh. you do? Why?

1095
00:51:41.973 --> 00:51:44.226
Because you've deliberately       
 substituted the word "sick."

1096
00:51:44.267 --> 00:51:46.853
which is a loose--                
 a polarizing--                    
                          Have I?

1097
00:51:46.895 --> 00:51:48.605
A what word. Doctor?          
                      Polarizing.

1098
00:51:48.647 --> 00:51:50.440
A polarizing word.            
              I never said "sick."

1099
00:51:50.482 --> 00:51:53.276
My grasp of the requirements      
 of command is adequate.

1100
00:51:53.318 --> 00:51:56.071
or I would have                   
 disqualified myself               
 from serving on the board.

1101
00:51:56.113 --> 00:51:57.781
Maybe you should                  
 have disqualified yourself.

1102
00:51:57.823 --> 00:51:59.491
Objection!                        
 The witness is being badgered!

1103
00:51:59.533 --> 00:52:01.618
I withdraw                
          my last statement.

1104
00:52:01.660 --> 00:52:03.537
No further questions.

1105
00:52:03.578 --> 00:52:06.206
Doctor. the defense counsel   
      has managed to put            
      words into your mouth

1106
00:52:06.248 --> 00:52:08.542
that I'm certain 
                  you don't mean.

1107
00:52:08.583 --> 00:52:11.419
I'm not aware that                
 he succeeded in putting           
 any words into my mouth.

1108
00:52:11.461 --> 00:52:14.464
Doctor. he drew               
      the implication from you      
      that Captain Queeg is sick.

1109
00:52:14.506 --> 00:52:17.634
Surely you don't--    
 I'm careful in my use             
 of terminology.

1110
00:52:17.676 --> 00:52:20.846
I did not use the term "sick."

1111
00:52:20.887 --> 00:52:25.684
Captain Queeg is definitely       
 not disabled for command.         
 which is the only issue here.

1112
00:52:28.770 --> 00:52:30.313
Prosecution rests.

1113
00:52:32.023 --> 00:52:33.650
Defense.              
              present your case.

1114
00:52:34.860 --> 00:52:36.653
I call the accused.

1115
00:52:38.029 --> 00:52:41.741
Does the accused request that     
 he be permitted to testify?       
                      Yes. sir.

1116
00:52:41.783 --> 00:52:43.785
You have the right        
          not to take the stand.

1117
00:52:43.827 --> 00:52:46.663
If you don't take the stand. 
      that fact won't be            
      to your prejudice.

1118
00:52:46.705 --> 00:52:50.333
If you take the stand.            
 you may be subjected to           
 a rigorous cross-examination.

1119
00:52:50.375 --> 00:52:52.252
I understand that.    
              sir.

1120
00:52:52.294 --> 00:52:54.212
You may take the stand.

1121
00:52:57.382 --> 00:52:59.885
State your name. rank             
 and present position.

1122
00:52:59.926 --> 00:53:01.303
Steven Maryk.             
          Lieutenant. US Navy.

1123
00:53:01.344 --> 00:53:03.180
executive officer         
          of the USS   Caine.

1124
00:53:03.221 --> 00:53:05.724
Are you the accused               
 in this court-martial?            
              Yes. I am.

1125
00:53:05.765 --> 00:53:08.143
What was your occupation          
 in civilian life?

1126
00:53:08.185 --> 00:53:10.937
Helping my father         
          in his fishing business. 
          We own a couple boats.

1127
00:53:10.979 --> 00:53:12.898
Where?                            
              San Francisco.

1128
00:53:12.939 --> 00:53:15.317
Then you were familiar            
 with the problems                 
 of ocean-going ship handling

1129
00:53:15.358 --> 00:53:17.152
prior to joining the Navy?

1130
00:53:17.194 --> 00:53:19.654
Yes. I've been on boats       
      since I was 14.

1131
00:53:19.696 --> 00:53:23.325
Did you relieve                   
 the commander of the USS   Caine    
 18th December. 2022?

1132
00:53:23.366 --> 00:53:25.410
Yes. I did.

1133
00:53:25.452 --> 00:53:27.996
Was the   Caine   in trouble          
 when you relieved its captain?    
                      Yes. it was.

1134
00:53:28.038 --> 00:53:31.541
And on what facts                 
 do you base that judgment?        
          Well. several things.

1135
00:53:31.583 --> 00:53:33.168
We couldn't hold course.

1136
00:53:33.210 --> 00:53:35.545
We broached three times   
          in an hour.               
 "Broached"?

1137
00:53:35.587 --> 00:53:39.174
Yes. wind and sea took charge     
 and tossed us sideways            
 ten minutes at a time.

1138
00:53:39.216 --> 00:53:42.052
We were rolling too steeply       
 for the inclinometer to record.

1139
00:53:42.093 --> 00:53:45.388
We were shipping water            
 out of the wheelhouse.            
 The generators were cutting out.

1140
00:53:45.430 --> 00:53:48.016
The ship was not responding   
      to emergency rudder           
      and engine settings.

1141
00:53:48.058 --> 00:53:49.517
We were lost              
          and out of control.

1142
00:53:49.559 --> 00:53:51.645
And did you inform                
 your captain of this?             
                      Yes.

1143
00:53:51.686 --> 00:53:55.732
Repeatedly for an hour.       
      I begged him                  
      to come north into the wind.

1144
00:53:55.774 --> 00:53:57.234
What was his reply?

1145
00:53:57.275 --> 00:54:00.737
Well. mostly          
              just a glazed look    
              and no answer.

1146
00:54:01.655 --> 00:54:03.490
Mr. Maryk.

1147
00:54:03.531 --> 00:54:07.327
when did you start                
 keeping your medical log          
 on Commander Queeg?

1148
00:54:07.369 --> 00:54:09.704
Shortly after the incident    
      with the mines                
      in the Straits of Hormuz.

1149
00:54:09.746 --> 00:54:13.500
And why did you start it?         
      I began to think the captain 
      might be mentally ill.

1150
00:54:13.541 --> 00:54:16.127
Why?                              
          Because of the yellow     
          dye marker business.

1151
00:54:16.169 --> 00:54:19.839
You mean the incident             
 where the commander acquired      
 the nickname Old Yellowstain?

1152
00:54:19.881 --> 00:54:21.091
Yes.

1153
00:54:21.132 --> 00:54:23.468
Were you an eyewitness            
 to this occurrence?

1154
00:54:23.510 --> 00:54:25.428
I was navigator.      
              I was right there     
              on the bridge.

1155
00:54:25.470 --> 00:54:28.056
Please describe                   
 this Yellowstain incident.

1156
00:54:29.391 --> 00:54:32.352
It was the third day 
              of an assigned sweep 
              with two other MCMs.

1157
00:54:32.394 --> 00:54:33.895
Mm-hmm.

1158
00:54:33.937 --> 00:54:36.731
We had detected               
      a field of acoustic mines.

1159
00:54:36.773 --> 00:54:38.733
[speaking louder]             
      It was the third day

1160
00:54:38.775 --> 00:54:40.777
of an assigned sweep          
      with two other MCMs.

1161
00:54:40.819 --> 00:54:42.779
We detected a field               
 of acoustic mines

1162
00:54:42.821 --> 00:54:44.781
in the narrowest part             
 of the strait

1163
00:54:44.823 --> 00:54:46.950
and we'd been ordered             
 to destroy them in place          
 using high explosives.

1164
00:54:46.992 --> 00:54:50.287
And that's delicate business.     
 It's gotta be done just right.

1165
00:54:50.328 --> 00:54:52.956
We milled around out there    
      for a while.

1166
00:54:52.998 --> 00:54:56.042
Then the captain decided 
          not to set the charges.

1167
00:54:56.084 --> 00:54:58.086
He gave us some excuse    
          about faulty equipment.

1168
00:54:58.128 --> 00:55:00.797
I checked the gear.               
 It was in perfect working order.

1169
00:55:00.839 --> 00:55:02.716
And the captain       
              wouldn't hear it.

1170
00:55:02.757 --> 00:55:05.260
He said the tech was incompetent 
 and he knew better.

1171
00:55:05.302 --> 00:55:08.054
So we dropped         
              a yellow dye marker   
              over the side.

1172
00:55:08.096 --> 00:55:10.223
radioed to the other MCM 
          to destroy the mines.

1173
00:55:10.265 --> 00:55:14.102
They radioed back                 
 to slow down. but we just--       
 we steamed right out of there.

1174
00:55:14.144 --> 00:55:15.478
[Greenwald] "Steamed."            
 Now. Mr. Maryk--

1175
00:55:15.520 --> 00:55:18.023
The court wishes to       
          question the witness.

1176
00:55:18.064 --> 00:55:21.776
Lieutenant. you say               
 the gear was in working order.    
 Did you check it personally?

1177
00:55:21.818 --> 00:55:24.362
Yes. sir. along with              
 the chief electronic tech         
 and the sonar men.

1178
00:55:24.404 --> 00:55:26.406
It was fine.                      
 There was absolutely              
 nothing wrong with the gear.

1179
00:55:26.448 --> 00:55:29.075
And after you steamed away.   
      was there any danger          
      due to shock waves

1180
00:55:29.117 --> 00:55:30.702
from the underwater   
              detonations?

1181
00:55:30.744 --> 00:55:32.829
No.                               
 No. there was not.

1182
00:55:32.871 --> 00:55:35.498
MCMs are designed to              
 withstand that kind of thing.     
 We do this all the time.

1183
00:55:35.540 --> 00:55:39.252
Now. you say these boats 
          signaled to you           
          to slow down.

1184
00:55:39.294 --> 00:55:41.921
Yes. sir.                         
          Was the signal reported   
          to your captain?

1185
00:55:41.963 --> 00:55:43.673
I reported it to him myself.

1186
00:55:43.715 --> 00:55:45.467
Was he aware that     
              he was steaming away

1187
00:55:45.508 --> 00:55:47.927
from his assigned spot    
          in the sweep formation?

1188
00:55:47.969 --> 00:55:50.513
It was obvious to                 
 everyone on the bridge.           
 I pointed it out.

1189
00:55:50.555 --> 00:55:52.682
I said we were breaking           
 the sweep pattern.

1190
00:55:52.724 --> 00:55:54.976
that the other vessels            
 would not know                    
 where we'd found the mines.

1191
00:55:55.018 --> 00:55:59.439
And that is when he said.         
 "We'll drop a yellow dye marker   
 over the side then."

1192
00:55:59.481 --> 00:56:01.358
You may continue.

1193
00:56:01.399 --> 00:56:04.736
Mr. Maryk. why didn't             
 you go immediately                
 to a higher authority

1194
00:56:04.778 --> 00:56:07.447
with your doubts                  
 about Captain Queeg's             
 mental health?

1195
00:56:07.489 --> 00:56:10.325
I felt if I had a record.     
      I'd be on stronger ground.

1196
00:56:10.367 --> 00:56:12.410
That's when I decided         
      to keep the medical log.

1197
00:56:12.452 --> 00:56:15.872
If I was wrong.                   
 I'd just burn it.                 
 I kept it under lock and key.

1198
00:56:15.914 --> 00:56:17.791
And what.                         
 in your opinion.

1199
00:56:17.832 --> 00:56:20.460
made an incident worthy           
 of keeping a record               
 in the medical log?

1200
00:56:20.502 --> 00:56:22.670
Any act that seemed           
      abnormal or strange.

1201
00:56:22.712 --> 00:56:24.714
Like what?                        
      Like the coffee machine.

1202
00:56:24.756 --> 00:56:26.299
The coffee machine                
 business?                         
              Yes.

1203
00:56:26.341 --> 00:56:28.134
Well. please describe             
 the coffee machine thing.

1204
00:56:28.176 --> 00:56:30.053
We had a new coffee machine   
      in the wardroom.

1205
00:56:30.095 --> 00:56:33.765
And. uh. Captain              
      really liked his coffee.      
      But you had to be careful.

1206
00:56:33.807 --> 00:56:36.309
You couldn't leave it             
 plugged in too long               
 or the thing would burn out.

1207
00:56:36.351 --> 00:56:38.520
That's exactly what happened.

1208
00:56:38.561 --> 00:56:40.814
One of the guys assigned          
 to the wardroom mess duty         
 forgot to unplug it

1209
00:56:40.855 --> 00:56:43.066
and the thing was--           
      it was just fried.

1210
00:56:43.108 --> 00:56:45.735
And none of them would admit      
 which one had done it.

1211
00:56:45.777 --> 00:56:49.406
So the captain ordered            
 all the officers of the ship      
 to sit as a trial of inquiry

1212
00:56:49.447 --> 00:56:51.366
to find out who'd burned out      
 the coffee machine.

1213
00:56:51.408 --> 00:56:55.036
Which-- Look. in itself.          
 it's a silly thing.

1214
00:56:55.078 --> 00:56:57.914
But this went on              
      for 36 hours.

1215
00:56:57.956 --> 00:56:59.249
[Greenwald whistles]

1216
00:56:59.290 --> 00:57:00.875
[Maryk]                           
 All ship's work suspended.

1217
00:57:00.917 --> 00:57:03.294
And there we are. all of us.      
 we're in the wardroom.

1218
00:57:03.336 --> 00:57:06.047
We're dying for sleep.        
      we need showers.

1219
00:57:06.089 --> 00:57:08.633
and we're trying to figure out    
 which one of these poor bastards 
 burned out the coffee machine.

1220
00:57:08.675 --> 00:57:11.970
And they're so scared.        
      they think whoever did it     
      is gonna get shot.

1221
00:57:12.011 --> 00:57:13.847
They'd have sooner died   
          before they told us.

1222
00:57:13.888 --> 00:57:16.266
And so. finally.          
          I go to the captain

1223
00:57:16.307 --> 00:57:19.394
and I say all the officers        
 will admit that they're           
 incompetent investigators

1224
00:57:19.436 --> 00:57:21.855
and take the hit                  
 on their fitness reports.

1225
00:57:21.896 --> 00:57:26.109
but we can't find out             
 who left the coffee machine       
 plugged in for too long.

1226
00:57:26.151 --> 00:57:29.279
And so he makes a mark            
 in his black book                 
 and he calls off the inquiry.

1227
00:57:29.320 --> 00:57:32.115
It's things like that.        
      Or the water business.

1228
00:57:32.157 --> 00:57:33.366
The water business.               
              Yes.

1229
00:57:33.408 --> 00:57:35.743
Please describe                   
 that water business.

1230
00:57:35.785 --> 00:57:39.914
Look. it's all in the log.    
 I know. but please describe       
 the water business.

1231
00:57:39.956 --> 00:57:42.709
The captain                   
      restricted water use          
      from the entire crew

1232
00:57:42.750 --> 00:57:44.711
for two days              
          in the middle             
          of a dust storm

1233
00:57:44.752 --> 00:57:48.381
because he caught             
      one of the deck gang          
      taking a shower.

1234
00:57:48.423 --> 00:57:51.342
Or it's plain crazy things.   
      Cheese business.

1235
00:57:51.384 --> 00:57:52.927
The cheese business.              
      The strawberry-- Yes.

1236
00:57:52.969 --> 00:57:56.055
Cheese business?      
              I don't recall        
              any cheese business.

1237
00:57:56.097 --> 00:57:59.225
This was on the first ship        
 the captain was assigned to.      
 sir. as an ensign.

1238
00:57:59.267 --> 00:58:02.437
Cheese was going missing          
 from the ship's stores.

1239
00:58:02.479 --> 00:58:04.647
And the captain investigated      
 and he caught a sailor

1240
00:58:04.689 --> 00:58:08.318
who'd made a duplicate key        
 to the padlock                    
 to the refrigerator.

1241
00:58:08.359 --> 00:58:10.487
Now. for catching                 
 this cheese thief.

1242
00:58:10.528 --> 00:58:12.697
he was given a letter             
 of commendation.

1243
00:58:12.739 --> 00:58:15.283
This is during peacetime.         
 so naturally                      
 he's pretty proud of the thing.

1244
00:58:15.325 --> 00:58:19.245
So when the strawberry stuff      
 started. he insisted              
 it was the same thing.

1245
00:58:19.287 --> 00:58:20.830
And all we had to do              
 was find the guy

1246
00:58:20.872 --> 00:58:23.791
who had made a duplicate key      
 to the wardroom fridge.

1247
00:58:23.833 --> 00:58:25.919
But of course                 
      that's ridiculous.

1248
00:58:25.960 --> 00:58:29.464
It was one of the guys assigned   
 to the wardroom mess again.

1249
00:58:29.506 --> 00:58:32.217
We all knew that they'd eaten     
 this quart of strawberries.

1250
00:58:32.258 --> 00:58:33.676
It was left over                  
 from the wardroom mess.

1251
00:58:33.718 --> 00:58:35.762
They were entitled to it.         
 That was the custom.

1252
00:58:35.803 --> 00:58:37.722
But when the captain              
 started to freak out              
 about those strawberries.

1253
00:58:37.764 --> 00:58:39.599
they froze up.                    
 said they didn't                  
 know who'd eaten them.

1254
00:58:39.641 --> 00:58:42.393
And the captain's                 
 so hot on his theory              
 he believes them.

1255
00:58:42.435 --> 00:58:44.562
So he ordered the search          
 for the key.                      
 Yes. sir.

1256
00:58:44.604 --> 00:58:49.317
We have never seen Captain Queeg 
 so happy before or since.

1257
00:58:49.359 --> 00:58:52.237
He's living the cheese business   
 all over again.

1258
00:58:52.278 --> 00:58:54.864
He organized the search himself.

1259
00:58:54.906 --> 00:58:57.492
We collected every key            
 on that ship.

1260
00:58:57.534 --> 00:59:01.287
We had just boxes--               
 barrels of keys.

1261
00:59:01.329 --> 00:59:03.373
That's about 2.800 of them        
 all told.

1262
00:59:03.414 --> 00:59:05.625
each tagged                       
 with the owner's name.

1263
00:59:05.667 --> 00:59:09.003
And just to be safe.              
 we searched that ship             
 from stem to stern.

1264
00:59:09.045 --> 00:59:11.673
from the radar mast           
      to the bilge.

1265
00:59:11.714 --> 00:59:13.091
We stripped the crew naked.

1266
00:59:13.132 --> 00:59:14.968
[Greenwald]                       
 Naked?                            
      Yes. sir. Naked.

1267
00:59:15.009 --> 00:59:17.428
Each one of them lined up.        
 stark naked.

1268
00:59:17.470 --> 00:59:19.722
and we shook out their clothes.

1269
00:59:19.764 --> 00:59:22.684
We searched their lockers.        
 We searched every hole.           
 every place on that ship.

1270
00:59:22.725 --> 00:59:25.353
We crawled under the bilge        
 and pulled out                    
 the lead ballast blocks

1271
00:59:25.395 --> 00:59:27.105
that are 200 pounds apiece.

1272
00:59:27.146 --> 00:59:30.316
This went on for three days.

1273
00:59:30.358 --> 00:59:32.360
[Greenwald]                       
 Three days?                       
 [Maryk] Yes. sir.

1274
00:59:32.402 --> 00:59:36.531
All in the name of a key          
 that never existed.

1275
00:59:36.573 --> 00:59:41.286
So. when I saw the captain    
      sitting by the fridge.

1276
00:59:41.327 --> 00:59:43.204
pulling keys one by one       
      from a barrel

1277
00:59:43.246 --> 00:59:47.667
and trying them in a padlock 
      for hours on end              
      with a gleam in his eye.

1278
00:59:47.709 --> 00:59:49.794
I gave up.

1279
00:59:49.836 --> 00:59:53.590
And that is when              
      I showed the medical log      
      to Lieutenant Keefer.

1280
00:59:54.757 --> 00:59:56.509
Mr. Maryk.

1281
00:59:56.551 --> 00:59:58.761
when Lieutenant Keefer    
          finished reading          
          your medical log.

1282
00:59:58.803 --> 01:00:01.097
what was              
              his first comment?

1283
01:00:01.848 --> 01:00:03.516
Sir. I don't remember.

1284
01:00:03.558 --> 01:00:06.311
Did he encourage you          
      to go to Admiral Williams?

1285
01:00:06.352 --> 01:00:08.271
No. sir.                          
 I did that on my own.

1286
01:00:08.313 --> 01:00:10.398
But he went with you 
              to the flagship.

1287
01:00:10.440 --> 01:00:14.110
Yes. sir.                 
      So. at first.                 
      he didn't discourage you?

1288
01:00:15.653 --> 01:00:18.448
Once we were                  
      aboard the flagship.          
      he discouraged me

1289
01:00:18.489 --> 01:00:20.950
and said we shouldn't             
 go through it and we didn't.

1290
01:00:20.992 --> 01:00:23.453
Would you say his testimony   
      on the subject was            
      substantially correct?

1291
01:00:23.494 --> 01:00:25.955
Yes. sir.                         
 This was all my doing. sir.

1292
01:00:25.997 --> 01:00:27.457
Continue your examination.

1293
01:00:27.498 --> 01:00:29.876
Mr. Maryk.                        
 when the cyclone was over.

1294
01:00:29.917 --> 01:00:32.795
did Commander Queeg               
 make an attempt                   
 to regain command?

1295
01:00:32.837 --> 01:00:34.589
Yes.

1296
01:00:34.631 --> 01:00:36.966
On the morning of the 19th.       
 after the storm had blown out.

1297
01:00:37.008 --> 01:00:38.468
What happened?

1298
01:00:39.844 --> 01:00:42.096
Well. I was in the chart house    
 writing up a dispatch.

1299
01:00:42.138 --> 01:00:44.974
And?                              
      I was reporting the relief    
      to Admiral Williams.

1300
01:00:45.016 --> 01:00:47.352
And?

1301
01:00:47.393 --> 01:00:50.355
Captain Queeg came and asked      
 if I would go to his cabin        
 and speak to him

1302
01:00:50.396 --> 01:00:52.315
before I sent the dispatch.

1303
01:00:52.357 --> 01:00:55.276
So I went below               
      and we talked.

1304
01:00:55.318 --> 01:00:57.236
And what happened?

1305
01:00:58.529 --> 01:01:02.325
It was the same as before.    
      uh. at first.

1306
01:01:02.367 --> 01:01:04.202
He said I'd be                    
 court-martialed for mutiny.

1307
01:01:04.243 --> 01:01:08.289
And then he went                  
 on this long thing about          
 how much he loved the Navy.

1308
01:01:08.331 --> 01:01:10.208
that he has no other interests.

1309
01:01:10.249 --> 01:01:13.503
and even if                       
 he was cleared of this            
 that his record would be ruined.

1310
01:01:13.544 --> 01:01:16.255
And I told him                
      I felt sorry for him.

1311
01:01:16.297 --> 01:01:18.174
And I-- I really did.

1312
01:01:19.884 --> 01:01:22.970
And that's when               
      he came out with              
      his proposal.

1313
01:01:23.012 --> 01:01:24.430
Which?

1314
01:01:25.807 --> 01:01:28.184
He said he wouldn't           
      write me up and report me.

1315
01:01:28.226 --> 01:01:30.144
that he would resume          
      command of the ship

1316
01:01:30.186 --> 01:01:33.314
and that the whole thing would    
 be written off and forgotten.

1317
01:01:33.356 --> 01:01:35.858
And what was your reply           
 to his proposal?

1318
01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.777
I was amazed.

1319
01:01:37.819 --> 01:01:40.863
I said. Captain.                  
 the whole ship knows about it.    
 [Greenwald] Yes.

1320
01:01:40.905 --> 01:01:43.157
It's written up               
      in the quartermaster's log.

1321
01:01:43.199 --> 01:01:45.368
It's written up               
      in the officer                
      of the deck's log.

1322
01:01:45.410 --> 01:01:48.913
And. uh--                     
      And he hemmed and hawed.

1323
01:01:48.955 --> 01:01:51.165
[Greenwald]                       
 And?

1324
01:01:51.207 --> 01:01:53.042
What happened next?

1325
01:01:53.084 --> 01:01:55.211
Finally. he said              
      it wouldn't be                
      the first time

1326
01:01:55.253 --> 01:01:58.172
that a rough log                  
 had been corrected                
 and fixed up after the fact.

1327
01:01:58.214 --> 01:02:00.842
Did you remind him                
 that the alteration of logs       
 is strictly forbidden?

1328
01:02:00.883 --> 01:02:03.428
Yes. I did.               
          And he kind of laughed.

1329
01:02:03.469 --> 01:02:05.930
He said it was either that    
      or a court-martial            
      for mutiny for me

1330
01:02:05.972 --> 01:02:08.766
and a black mark              
      on his record which he felt   
      he did not deserve.

1331
01:02:08.808 --> 01:02:10.017
And what followed?

1332
01:02:10.059 --> 01:02:11.978
He begged and he pleaded.

1333
01:02:12.019 --> 01:02:16.607
And. uh. at one point he cried    
 and eventually got very angry

1334
01:02:16.649 --> 01:02:18.359
and he ordered me out         
      of his cabin.

1335
01:02:18.401 --> 01:02:20.695
That is when                  
      I sent the dispatch.

1336
01:02:20.737 --> 01:02:25.199
Then you had the opportunity.     
 less than 24 hours later.

1337
01:02:25.241 --> 01:02:28.911
to expunge this whole event       
 from the official records

1338
01:02:28.953 --> 01:02:31.914
with your captain's               
 knowledge and approval.

1339
01:02:31.956 --> 01:02:33.583
Yes. sir.

1340
01:02:33.624 --> 01:02:36.753
Mr. Maryk.                        
 were you panicky at all           
 during the storm?

1341
01:02:36.794 --> 01:02:38.546
No. I was not.

1342
01:02:38.588 --> 01:02:42.592
Lieutenant. you are charged       
 with relieving                    
 your captain willfully.

1343
01:02:42.633 --> 01:02:47.430
without authority                 
 and without justifiable cause.

1344
01:02:47.472 --> 01:02:49.432
Did you relieve                   
 Commander Queeg willfully?

1345
01:02:49.474 --> 01:02:52.435
Yes.                          
      I knew what I was doing.

1346
01:02:52.477 --> 01:02:54.729
Did you relieve him               
 without authority?

1347
01:02:54.771 --> 01:02:57.607
No. my authority is Chapter 11    
 of Navy Regulations.

1348
01:02:57.648 --> 01:03:00.943
Did you relieve                   
 without justifiable cause?        
                  No.

1349
01:03:00.985 --> 01:03:03.488
My justifiable cause was          
 the captain's mental breakdown

1350
01:03:03.529 --> 01:03:05.531
at a time when the ship       
      was in danger.

1351
01:03:05.573 --> 01:03:08.451
Thank you.                
          No further questions.

1352
01:03:10.077 --> 01:03:13.831
Mr. Maryk.                
          this amazing interview

1353
01:03:13.873 --> 01:03:17.668
in which the captain offered 
      to falsify official records.

1354
01:03:17.710 --> 01:03:19.754
were there            
              any witnesses to it?

1355
01:03:20.630 --> 01:03:22.799
We were alone in his cabin.       
 No.

1356
01:03:22.840 --> 01:03:25.843
This incident with the mines.     
 Did anyone else                   
 see these records?

1357
01:03:25.885 --> 01:03:27.970
Which. according to you.          
 indicated that the   Caine

1358
01:03:28.012 --> 01:03:29.931
had departed                      
 her assigned sweep formation?

1359
01:03:29.972 --> 01:03:32.809
Was there anything        
          in the records            
          of the ship's movements

1360
01:03:32.850 --> 01:03:35.394
that would verify     
              that departure?

1361
01:03:35.436 --> 01:03:37.313
Well. about an hour               
 after it happened.

1362
01:03:37.355 --> 01:03:40.066
the captain asked                 
 to see the chart.                 
 he took it to his cabin.

1363
01:03:40.107 --> 01:03:42.777
and when I got the log back.      
 there was no mention              
 of the incident.

1364
01:03:42.819 --> 01:03:46.239
Right. Then you have          
      no corroboration              
      of this story.

1365
01:03:46.280 --> 01:03:48.574
No.                           
      [clears throat]

1366
01:03:48.616 --> 01:03:52.662
Mr. Maryk. who coined             
 the nickname Old Yellowstain?

1367
01:03:52.703 --> 01:03:55.164
That just sprung              
      into existence.

1368
01:03:55.206 --> 01:03:57.959
Throughout the ship   
              or just among         
              the officers?

1369
01:03:58.000 --> 01:03:59.335
Just among the officers.

1370
01:03:59.377 --> 01:04:01.712
You sure you didn't   
              coin it yourself?

1371
01:04:01.754 --> 01:04:03.005
I didn't.

1372
01:04:03.881 --> 01:04:08.803
What kind of rating           
      would you give yourself       
      for loyalty to your captain?

1373
01:04:08.845 --> 01:04:11.305
I'd say                           
 I was a loyal officer.

1374
01:04:12.265 --> 01:04:15.476
Did you issue                     
 a 72-hour liberty

1375
01:04:15.518 --> 01:04:18.563
to Petty Officer Stilwell         
 in December

1376
01:04:18.604 --> 01:04:21.649
against your captain's            
 express instructions?

1377
01:04:21.691 --> 01:04:23.734
Yes. 
 You call that                     
 a loyal act?

1378
01:04:23.776 --> 01:04:24.819
No.

1379
01:04:24.861 --> 01:04:27.572
Then you admit to                 
 a disloyal act

1380
01:04:27.613 --> 01:04:30.116
in your first days                
 as executive officer.

1381
01:04:30.157 --> 01:04:31.576
Yes.

1382
01:04:31.617 --> 01:04:35.538
Mr. Maryk. where did you          
 get your schooling?

1383
01:04:35.580 --> 01:04:37.290
Public schools.   
                  San Francisco.    
              Okay.

1384
01:04:37.331 --> 01:04:38.958
And San Francisco     
              State University.

1385
01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:41.544
And how were your grades          
 in elementary school?

1386
01:04:41.586 --> 01:04:43.462
[scoffs]          
                  They were okay.

1387
01:04:43.504 --> 01:04:46.841
Average? Above average?           
 Below average?

1388
01:04:46.883 --> 01:04:47.884
Average.

1389
01:04:47.925 --> 01:04:50.219
How about your                    
 high school grades?

1390
01:04:50.261 --> 01:04:53.890
Well. I didn't do     
              so good there.        
              Uh. below average.

1391
01:04:54.849 --> 01:04:57.226
What kind of courses              
 did you take in college?

1392
01:04:57.268 --> 01:04:58.394
Business courses.

1393
01:04:58.436 --> 01:05:00.062
Any pre-medical courses?          
                          No.

1394
01:05:00.104 --> 01:05:03.399
Any psychology?                   
 Any psychiatry courses?           
                              No.

1395
01:05:03.441 --> 01:05:05.359
How were your grades      
          in college?               
                          They--

1396
01:05:05.401 --> 01:05:08.529
I got by.     
                  Below average?

1397
01:05:09.155 --> 01:05:11.282
[Maryk]   
                          Yes.

1398
01:05:11.324 --> 01:05:14.827
[Challee] Where did you   
          get these ideas           
          about paranoia?

1399
01:05:14.869 --> 01:05:18.331
Prob-- Well. books.           
      And. uh... [clears throat]    
      ...a lot of research online.

1400
01:05:18.372 --> 01:05:20.750
Books? What books?    
              Name the titles.      
              Which websites?

1401
01:05:20.791 --> 01:05:23.336
They're medical type books        
 about mental illness.

1402
01:05:23.377 --> 01:05:26.213
and I-I don't remember            
 the exact names of the sites.

1403
01:05:26.255 --> 01:05:29.675
Oh. Was this                  
      your intellectual hobby.      
      reading about psychiatry?

1404
01:05:29.717 --> 01:05:31.969
No.                       
              Well. then where did 
              you get these books?

1405
01:05:32.011 --> 01:05:35.056
Fr-- I borrowed them              
 from. uh. ships' doctors          
 here and there.

1406
01:05:35.097 --> 01:05:39.226
[chuckles]                    
      And with your background.     
      your scholastic record.

1407
01:05:39.268 --> 01:05:43.189
you imagine that you understood   
 these highly technical            
 and scientific works?

1408
01:05:43.230 --> 01:05:45.107
I got something out of them.

1409
01:05:45.149 --> 01:05:47.401
What is                   
          a conditioned reflex?

1410
01:05:47.443 --> 01:05:48.945
I don't know.

1411
01:05:48.986 --> 01:05:50.905
What is schizophrenia?

1412
01:05:50.947 --> 01:05:53.074
Uh. I think it's--                
 it's a mental illness.

1413
01:05:53.115 --> 01:05:54.408
You think so?     
              Yes.

1414
01:05:54.450 --> 01:05:56.911
What are its symptoms?        
                  I don't know.

1415
01:05:56.953 --> 01:06:00.539
In fact. you don't know           
 what you're talking about         
 when you discuss mental illness.

1416
01:06:00.581 --> 01:06:03.876
Is that right?    
 Well. you know. I never said      
 I knew much about it.

1417
01:06:03.918 --> 01:06:04.919
[chuckles]

1418
01:06:04.961 --> 01:06:06.504
Have you ever heard               
 the expression

1419
01:06:06.545 --> 01:06:08.547
that a little learning            
 is a dangerous thing?

1420
01:06:08.965 --> 01:06:10.591
Yes.

1421
01:06:10.633 --> 01:06:12.718
You had a head full of terms      
 you didn't understand.

1422
01:06:12.760 --> 01:06:15.262
and on that basis                 
 felt you had the right

1423
01:06:15.304 --> 01:06:17.640
to depose                         
 a commanding officer

1424
01:06:17.682 --> 01:06:19.767
on the grounds                    
 of mental illness.

1425
01:06:19.809 --> 01:06:22.520
Is that right?    
 I didn't relieve Captain Queeg    
 because what the book said.

1426
01:06:22.561 --> 01:06:26.816
I relieved him because the ship   
 was in danger of sinking.         
          No. never mind the ship.

1427
01:06:26.857 --> 01:06:29.568
We are discussing             
      your grasp of psychiatry.     
          Mm-hmm.

1428
01:06:29.610 --> 01:06:34.323
Did you hear the diagnosis        
 of the qualified psychiatrist     
 who examined your captain?

1429
01:06:34.365 --> 01:06:36.158
Yes. 
 And what was                      
 their diagnosis?

1430
01:06:36.200 --> 01:06:38.995
Was he crazy or wasn't he         
 on December 18th?

1431
01:06:39.036 --> 01:06:40.663
They say he wasn't.

1432
01:06:40.705 --> 01:06:43.249
But you.                  
          with your whining gripes 
          of strawberries

1433
01:06:43.290 --> 01:06:46.419
and coffee makers.    
              know better.

1434
01:06:46.460 --> 01:06:50.172
Mr. Maryk. who was            
      the third ranking officer     
      on your ship?

1435
01:06:50.214 --> 01:06:51.674
Lieutenant Keefer.

1436
01:06:51.716 --> 01:06:53.759
Was he            
                  a good officer?   
          Yes.

1437
01:06:53.801 --> 01:06:56.512
Do you consider his mind 
          as good as yours?

1438
01:06:56.554 --> 01:06:58.931
Yes. Uh. better. 
          Better.

1439
01:06:58.973 --> 01:07:02.101
Did you show              
          your medical log to him? 
 Yes.

1440
01:07:02.143 --> 01:07:05.604
Was he convinced by it    
          that the captain          
          was mentally ill?

1441
01:07:06.188 --> 01:07:08.065
No.

1442
01:07:08.107 --> 01:07:10.943
He talked to you          
          out of trying to have     
          the captain relieved.

1443
01:07:10.985 --> 01:07:12.028
Yes.

1444
01:07:12.069 --> 01:07:14.030
And yet two weeks later.

1445
01:07:14.071 --> 01:07:17.283
despite the whole weight 
          of naval discipline.

1446
01:07:17.324 --> 01:07:20.453
despite the arguments     
          of the next officer       
          in rank to you.

1447
01:07:20.494 --> 01:07:22.455
a superior intellect.

1448
01:07:22.496 --> 01:07:24.373
despite all this.

1449
01:07:24.415 --> 01:07:27.918
you went ahead        
              and seized command    
              of your ship?

1450
01:07:29.336 --> 01:07:31.047
I relieved Captain Queeg

1451
01:07:31.088 --> 01:07:32.965
because he definitely             
 seemed sick

1452
01:07:33.007 --> 01:07:35.384
on the morning                
      of the cyclone.

1453
01:07:35.426 --> 01:07:38.679
You still believe     
              that your diagnosis   
              of Captain Queeg

1454
01:07:38.721 --> 01:07:40.765
is superior       
                  to the doctors'?

1455
01:07:40.806 --> 01:07:44.060
J-- O-Only about Queeg            
 on the morning                    
 of the cyclone.

1456
01:07:46.312 --> 01:07:48.064
No more questions.

1457
01:07:50.399 --> 01:07:51.942
No re-examination.

1458
01:07:53.319 --> 01:07:54.904
You may step down.        
          Lieutenant.

1459
01:08:02.787 --> 01:08:05.539
Call                              
 Lieutenant Commander Queeg.

1460
01:08:14.924 --> 01:08:18.469
Commander. you are reminded       
 that you are still under oath.

1461
01:08:18.511 --> 01:08:20.888
Yes. sir.                 
                      Be seated.

1462
01:08:23.349 --> 01:08:25.684
Commander. on the morning         
 of the 19th December.

1463
01:08:25.725 --> 01:08:28.729
did you have an interview         
 in your room                      
 with Lieutenant Maryk?

1464
01:08:28.770 --> 01:08:30.106
Well. let's see.

1465
01:08:30.147 --> 01:08:33.024
The 19th.                     
      the day after the storm.

1466
01:08:33.067 --> 01:08:34.318
Yes. Yes. I did.

1467
01:08:34.359 --> 01:08:36.946
Was the interview                 
 at your request?                  
              Yes.

1468
01:08:36.987 --> 01:08:38.948
What was the substance            
 of the interview?

1469
01:08:38.988 --> 01:08:41.367
Well. as I say.               
      I felt sorry for him.

1470
01:08:41.408 --> 01:08:43.786
Hated to see him              
      ruining his life

1471
01:08:43.828 --> 01:08:46.287
over one panicky mistake.

1472
01:08:46.330 --> 01:08:50.542
particularly knowing          
      that it was his ambition      
      to make the Navy a career.

1473
01:08:50.584 --> 01:08:53.629
I tried as hard as I could    
      to show him                   
      what a mistake he had made.

1474
01:08:53.671 --> 01:08:56.090
suggested                     
      he relinquish command         
      back to me

1475
01:08:56.131 --> 01:08:58.591
and offered to be             
      as lenient as possible

1476
01:08:58.634 --> 01:09:00.426
when reporting                
      what had happened.

1477
01:09:00.469 --> 01:09:03.305
You never offered                 
 not to report the incident?       
                      How could I?

1478
01:09:03.346 --> 01:09:06.475
It had already been       
          recorded in the logs.     
          Yes.

1479
01:09:06.517 --> 01:09:09.103
Those logs.                   
      were they handwritten.        
      typed. or what?

1480
01:09:09.145 --> 01:09:10.938
It wouldn't have      
              made a difference.

1481
01:09:10.979 --> 01:09:13.858
Were they handwritten.            
 Commander?                        
          Well. probably.

1482
01:09:13.899 --> 01:09:16.068
Quartermasters log. OOD.

1483
01:09:16.109 --> 01:09:18.194
Rough logs                        
 are usually handwritten.

1484
01:09:18.237 --> 01:09:21.573
I can't imagine                   
 that the yeoman had time          
 to type out smooth logs.

1485
01:09:21.615 --> 01:09:23.408
given all the excitement.

1486
01:09:23.450 --> 01:09:26.120
Did you offer                 
      to alter the logs             
      and not report the incident?

1487
01:09:26.162 --> 01:09:28.413
No. I did not.                    
 Alterations are not permitted.

1488
01:09:28.455 --> 01:09:30.499
Lieutenant Maryk          
          testified under oath.     
          Commander.

1489
01:09:30.541 --> 01:09:32.585
that you made     
                  such an offer.

1490
01:09:32.626 --> 01:09:36.380
Not only that. but you        
      begged and pleaded with him   
      to alter the logs.

1491
01:09:36.421 --> 01:09:39.841
in return for which       
          you promised to hush up   
          the story completely

1492
01:09:39.884 --> 01:09:41.510
and make no report.

1493
01:09:41.551 --> 01:09:43.220
Well. that's just                 
 not the truth.

1494
01:09:43.261 --> 01:09:45.639
There isn't any truth     
          in it at all?

1495
01:09:45.680 --> 01:09:48.725
It's a complete distortion        
 of what I've said.                
 My version is the exact truth.

1496
01:09:48.767 --> 01:09:51.687
You deny the proposal     
          to alter the logs         
          and hush up the story.

1497
01:09:51.729 --> 01:09:53.647
Yes. I deny it completely.

1498
01:09:53.689 --> 01:09:56.483
Th-That's the part                
 that he's made up.                
 the crying and the pleading.

1499
01:09:56.525 --> 01:09:57.818
It's fantastic.

1500
01:09:57.860 --> 01:09:59.653
You're accusing Mr. Maryk     
      of perjury.

1501
01:09:59.695 --> 01:10:01.447
I-I'm not accusing him--

1502
01:10:01.488 --> 01:10:02.823
[laughs]

1503
01:10:02.865 --> 01:10:04.950
He's accused of enough            
 as it stands.

1504
01:10:04.992 --> 01:10:07.786
I'm just saying you'll hear       
 a lot of strange things           
 about me from Maryk.

1505
01:10:07.828 --> 01:10:10.206
Th-That's all I'm saying.

1506
01:10:10.247 --> 01:10:13.542
Isn't it obvious. Commander.      
 that one of you is not telling    
 the truth about this meeting?

1507
01:10:13.584 --> 01:10:16.629
Well. it appears so.              
              Can you prove that    
              it isn't you?

1508
01:10:16.670 --> 01:10:20.216
Only by citing                    
 a clean record of 21 years        
 as a naval officer

1509
01:10:20.257 --> 01:10:24.053
over the word of                  
 a man standing trial              
 for a mutinous act.

1510
01:10:25.763 --> 01:10:30.559
Commander. did you ever           
 receive $1.000 from               
 Lieutenant Junior Grade Keith?

1511
01:10:30.601 --> 01:10:32.853
Uh. I don't recall offhand.

1512
01:10:32.895 --> 01:10:35.397
He testified you did.             
              I did?                
              On what occasion?

1513
01:10:35.439 --> 01:10:38.901
On the occasion of the loss   
      of a crate of yours           
      in the Port of Oman.

1514
01:10:38.943 --> 01:10:41.195
Oh. y-yes. Okay.              
      [chuckling] I remember that.

1515
01:10:41.237 --> 01:10:43.906
That's over a year ago.   
          December thereabouts.

1516
01:10:43.948 --> 01:10:46.575
He was responsible    
              for the loss.

1517
01:10:46.617 --> 01:10:50.246
Well. insisted        
              on paying for it.     
              a-a-and so he did.

1518
01:10:50.287 --> 01:10:53.290
And what was in this crate        
 that cost $1.000?

1519
01:10:53.332 --> 01:10:56.043
Well. uniforms. books.

1520
01:10:56.085 --> 01:10:59.088
n-navigating instruments.     
      the usual things.

1521
01:10:59.129 --> 01:11:00.923
How was Keith responsible?

1522
01:11:00.965 --> 01:11:03.217
Well. he was the boat officer.    
 He was responsible for loading.

1523
01:11:03.259 --> 01:11:06.595
He issued foolish.        
          contradictory orders      
          that rattled the men.

1524
01:11:06.637 --> 01:11:08.681
They dropped the crate        
